  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "If you get married in the US, your Argentinean boyfriend can apply for a marriage-based green card (permanent residency). Here's an overview of the process:\n\n1. **Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative)**: You would need to file this petition with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) on behalf of your boyfriend. This step establishes your relationship and seeks to bring him to the U.S. as a permanent resident.\n\n2. **Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status)**: If he is already in the U.S. (admitted or paroled), he can file this application simultaneously with the I-130 petition. If he is outside the U.S., he will go through consular processing overseas after the I-130 is approved.\n\n3. **Work Authorization**: He can apply for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) using Form I-765 while his I-485 application is being processed. Typically, it may take a few months (around 3-6 months) to receive the EAD after submission, allowing him to work in the U.S. legally while his green card application is pending.\n\n4. **Final Steps**: Once the I-485 is approved, he will receive his green card.\n\nProcessing times can vary based on individual circumstances and the USCIS backlog, so it's essential to check the current processing times on the USCIS website. Overall, the timeline for obtaining work authorization can be around 3-10 months, depending on how quickly the applications are processed.",
